author: Marcus Salem
comment_text: I've had this car 18 months now and have got to properly test it in this recent heavy snow. It's still got the factory tyres which are Continental Cross Contacts so not winter tyres, and they are fairly worn now. I live right out in the countryside where the snow drifts horrendously. Been out the last couple of days and the car has performed amazingly. Had to use Lock mode a few times to extract the car and also get it up some short but very steep inclines. Although it did slide around quite a bit (due to the tyres) and needed some heavy throttle it got through any situation I put it in. Granted, it won't plough through snow drifts like a Discovery but it tunnels its way through with a bit of throttle. With winter tyres or something like Nokian Weatherproofs I can imagine the Vitara will be phenomenal. It's completely justified itself to me as a purchase as it's not the cheapest car for it's size but it is loaded with kit.

author: Megadriver
comment_text: This is one of the WORST cars I've ever driven... Honestly, things I'd rather do than drive one of these include: Setting myself on fire, joining a vegan protest and working at a supermarket. The interior plastics are terrible. Very cheap, very ugly, very nasty to the touch. And get this... The door panel moves when you close, or open the window! What car does that?! And I'm not done with the windows. The Vitara has a button to lock the windows and prevent passengers from opening them like every other car, but... Here is the catch, you can't operate passenger windows either! Dumbest design ever. You have to unlock the passenger windows before you (the driver) can operate them and the passenger windows are not automatic! What car doesn't have one-touch automatic windows in 2017?! The folding mirrors are noisy, the automatic gear lever sounds horrible when you move it, the parking sensor sound is too loud and sounds like a life support machine. The roof lining isn't soft enough and the sun visors are plastic and feel brittle. And touch screen volume?! Terrible idea.   The automatic gearbox is garbage. It shifts as rough as a city bus, it hesitates and to get kickdown, you need to really stomp on the gas pedal. There is little sound insulation so the harder you drive the Vitara, the more noise you get. I'd hate to drive this down the Autobahn at 200+ kmh and try to have a conversation with someone.   For the price of a base model Vitara, I can buy loads of better cars. I can even buy an S-class!

comment_text: Scotty you don't know everything man! Many years ago I bought a new Pontiac Firefly (Suzuki) with the 3 cylinder engine and a five speed transmission. author: C. Walker
comment_text: "It would have been nice 5 minute video titled ""The Truth About Suzuki Cars and Why They Stopped Making Them in the US"" would have been about Suzuki cars for more than a sentence or two. I also had no idea that they were ever made in the US.  For those interested, the reason why Suzuki left they US market likely had far more to do with the softness of the market, competition and the amount of marketing capital Suzuki either wasn't willing or didn't have to spend.   I, for one, still think SoA did itself a disservice by not opening Suzuki only stores that offered all of their consumer products (ATVs, motorcycles, marine, automobiles) in a few high-visibility markets. I suspect the new Jimny will be their re-entry in the American market. I think they might actually being able to market is successfully as an off-road only vehicle, but if they could get it past the Feds, it would be attractive to the outdoorsy/minimalist set. author: alain gautier
comment_text: Happy owner of an SSS, I enjoy its low weight, very flexible motor with a generous torque, driving smoothness, good soundproofing, maneuverability, comfort/road-handling ratio, habitability and plethora of equipment.  However I blame this car for : * No digital speedometer !! (especially since it offers a lot of other useless informations) * Cannot automatically fold mirrors from the outside * Mostly for a sport car, the silhouette should be lower, as well as the ground clearance (16 inch rims would help) * I would prefer a more inclined windshield, wider glazed surfaces, lower waistline, less ostentatious style (as on the Up Gti, prettier although 1 foot smaller) * The first gear is really too short * Ridiculous horn, especially considering its aggressive look : imagine Schwartzy speaking with Omer Simpson's voice ;-) * A sliding rear seat (as on my old ForFour) would be a very good idea

author: Stevan V
comment_text: Awesome review! Unfortunately, based on personal experience keep away from this vehicle. I purchased a top spec Vitara in January 2019, the front-wheel drive 1.4L Boosterjet engine version with a six-speed auto. Gotta say one of the worst cars I've ever owned. The build quality is substandard. Poor plastics aside, the carpet has literally been stapled to chassis, while the interior trim is barely holding together. I have already been back to the dealership on two occasions. The plastic cover underneath the rear right door has already come loose and the plastic in the steering wheel infuriatingly vibrates at a high pitch at 2000 revs?! Not to mention the fact that the when the vehicle is turned off the engine/exhaust system produces a loud popping noise for 5-10 minutes. It's also very irritating when attempting to shut the doors, and especially the boot.. rarely do they close at the first attempt. Considering how much cash I forked out for this lemon, I am not a happy camper. Caveat emptor guys!

author: Richard Smith
comment_text: I‚Äôve got the 2016 Vitara S automatic. What the reviewer failed to mention is the huge fun to be had in Sport. You can really feel it tighten in response as the power is sent to the rear wheels, and it becomes really quite quick. Acceleration is practically instant when just kissing the throttle and it is brilliant. Note to buyers, remember to only change the mode when the wheels are pointing straight ahead, you don‚Äôt want the transmission to get stuck in a knot. The handbook mentions this of course. Oh, and the annual servicing on mine is just what I want, a direct injection turbo must have it‚Äôs oil changed regularly. All cars should have annual oil changes anyway. Another thing, three years and nothing has gone wrong, nothing. I forgot, we had to drive a new Mokka for week at work, they are horrible; terrible unsettled ride, poor visibility, cramped and zero fun. Just saying...

author: Florin Cretu
comment_text: Great and detailed review, congratulations for a job well done. I've bought myself last month a 1.4 AllGrip automatic version, fully equipped and I'm very happy with it so far. On highway it practically runs alone, follows the front car if the case or accelerates alone if you change lanes and also has all kinds of sensors and warnings to keep you out of troubles. On Sport mode it accelerates like hell if you push it:). The wide sunroof is a blessing, my kids are delighted with it because of the light and the view. I got it with a thin spare tire that fits perfectly and doesn't eat into space, plus that you have extra space around it to store other smaller items.

Thanks for the video. All the best!

comment_text: "This entire series about the motorbikes must be made by the same people who are responsible for the History Channel. The program unfortunately is geared towards the American markets rather than the critical thinking of the rest of the world. The Americans prefer fantasy and happy endings rather than the truth. author: Steve bogert
comment_text: The 250 cc Hustler was not impressive compared to the Kawasaki Samurai 250 twin. Their 500 cc Titan got a reputation more for reliability than for performance especially compared to the Kawasaki Mach 3, so did their 2 stroke triples! By then Yamaha had begun to sell 4 stroke models. Suzuki was the last to sell 4 stroke bikes, they did get to learn a lot by watching their competitors. Presumably that is why the first GS 750 was so exceptional.  The early GSXR was described as 'air cooled'. in fact they were liquid cooled by engine oil! Like other brand's 600 sport models, the GSXR 600 was always related to the GSXR 400, a model popular in Japan but not in the west.

author: Cajon Jackie
comment_text: "My relationship with Suzuki goes back to the very early 70's. After the 50cc my brother and myself JUMPED up to the 500cc then the 750cc which got bored out to an amazingly fast almost 1000cc Cafe Racer after being push into a swimming pool by unknown vandals for unknown reasons. After that I bought the 550 cubic centimeter GSL which, with wheels instead of spokes, a step seat instead of a flat bench, slightly pulled back, instead of almost straight across, handle bars and a ""Fat Bob-esque"" gas tank instead of what they were before 1980, that bike, which had rarely ever been seen by anybody out there, got me shit loads of complements. I always answered by ""Thanks, I built it myself.""  Well, marriage made me slow down a bit so I took up Sport Fishing but continued my relationship with Suzuki by buying one of their outboard motors. What can I say? They were outstanding motors which were very forgiving for the forgetful. Like when Brother-in-law forgot to put any oil in the gas. It started choking sputtering coughing then died. It was then I discovered the problem but I guessed ""It's too late, the engine is blown"" but, after adding the 2 cycle engine oil to the gas and giving it a few shakes to mix it that Suzuki 50 HP started on the first crank. I as amazed, to say the least!  I'm still not done with my ""I Love Suzuki Anythings"" story because, after Outboard motors for fishing, my wife wanted ""A NEW car instead of my husband giving me another hand-me-down Silverado while HE gets a Brand New Silverado which, because I'm short, I can't see across a trucks hood anyway SO I WANT A CAR ""I"" PICKED OUT""  She did, the Suzuki Areo, a tiny car, but a shit load of fun after driving trucks for so long and it had a tiny price tag which made me happy still with her selection. Well, this story don't turn out as this story might indicate because I became disabled by a genetic disorder called CMT disease that put me in a wheel chair and the Areo became just too small for a large man, a small wife, a child and a wheel chair. Then? LOL the shit REALLY hit the fan for my wife by her getting, not one, but 3 types of cancer. So I'm disabled with a disabled wife and now own the most expensive Suzuki I ever bought, a 26,000$ Grand Vitara that the Areo helped pay for, and GOD the Vitara is a big pile of shit that just keeps breaking down, again and again with MAJOR problems such as Blown head gaskets and the last time it broke down Suzuki denied it was their problem at all (Stalling), their excuse being ""It's in the cooling system"", then, after ensuring it wasn't the cooling system but rather, another blown head gasket, which I KNEW and suspected they knew all along (MORE stalling), I had the vehicle carried by towing truck to Suzuki, with my mechanic in-tow to testify to the facts as he knew them, only to find out that Suzuki Automobiles of America was gone, vamoosed, No longer in business, forget about getting any help from Suzuki because we, ""Suzuki Automobiles of North America"" don't have any business's left in North America!!  So, bottom line and without even an apology or reach around from Suzuki, and though the Vitara had THREE YEARS of warranty left to run on it, I had to trade in the Suzuki getting NOTHING as trade in value and now I have a monthly car note I can barely afford to pay. They're right, you know? There IS a thin line between Love and Hate and I'm going to my grave HATING THOSE MOTHER FUCKER AT Suzuki for fucking over, during our greatest need for honest business and businessmen, my cancerous wife and diseased self, then, for as long as I live I'll tell people  ""Don't buy anything from Suzuki, you'll get fucked in the ass, I DID AND LET ME TELL YOU HOW"""

author: Stevan V
comment_text: Purchased a top spec Vitara in January 2019, the front-wheel drive 1.4L Boosterjet engine version with a six-speed auto. Gotta say one of the worst cars I've ever owned. The build quality is substandard. Poor plastics aside, the carpet has literally been stapled to chassis, while the interior trim is barely holding together. I have already been back to the dealership on two occasions. The plastic cover underneath the rear right door has already come loose and the plastic in the steering wheel infuriatingly vibrates at a high pitch at 2000 revs?! Not to mention the fact that the when the vehicle is turned off the engine/exhaust system produces a loud cracking noise for 5-10 minutes. It's also very irritating when attempting to shut the doors, and especially the boot.. rarely do they close at the first attempt. Considering how much cash I forked out for this lemon, I am not a happy camper.

author: Federico Vargiu
comment_text: Devo farti i complimenti, guido la nuova Sport da ormai 3 mesi e mi ritrovo praticamente in ogni punto della tua recensione. Il clacson ho gi√† provveduto a cambiarlo, lo scarico sar√† il prossimo passo, per i consumi purtroppo abitando in citt√† i miei sono nettamente peggiori dei tuoi (13,5-14,00 km/l) per colpa dei mille semafori rossi piazzati ogni cento metri, per√≤ la descrizione che hai fornito su prestazioni, assetto e comfort la trovo perfettamente allineata al mio parere. L'unica precisazione che vorrei fare √® sui valori dichiarati, dove Suzuki da diversi anni sta dichiarando su tutte le sue vetture dei valori molto pessimistici: su questa Swift, in piano e partendo da fermo col piede giusto, cambiando in modo perfetto e veloce, si riesce a stare sui 7 secondi spaccati contro gli 8,1 dichiarati, mentre per la velocit√† massima concordo con quanto riscontrato in una prova di una testata automobilistica che ha rilevato 216 km/h effettivi. In ogni caso √® un auto veramente entusiasmante sotto molti punti di vista, provatela se potete perch√® non vi deluder√† e, se decideste di acquistarla, vi accorgerete presto che vale fino all'ultimo centesimo del prezzo che ha (18.150 euro approfittando dello sconto Suzuki).

comment_text: "Ich bin ein gro√üer Suzuki Fan, wohl wissend das die Bikes nie an die Materialqualit√§t, das Finish und die Details anderer japanischer Marken herankam, wie etwa Honda oder Yamaha.
